Task: Create compressed archive of developer jim's data from /data/jim and transfer to /home.

Task Overview
Environment: Stratos DC, Nautilus storage server

Objective: Archive /data/jim directory as jim.tar.gz and move to /home

User: natasha (sudo access)
​

Prerequisites
SSH access to storage server (e.g., ststor01.stratos.xfusioncorp.com)

Root/sudo privileges

Step-by-Step Solution
1. Access Storage Server
bash
# From jump host
ssh natasha@ststor01.stratos.xfusioncorp.com
sudo -i
2. Verify Source Directory
bash
ls -l /data/jim
3. Create Compressed Archive
bash
tar -czvf /root/jim.tar.gz /data/jim
Flags explained:

-c: Create new archive

-z: Gzip compression

-v: Verbose output

-f: Specify filename
​

4. Transfer to /home
bash
mv /root/jim.tar.gz /home/
5. Validation
bash
ls -lh /home/jim.tar.gz
tar -tzf /home/jim.tar.gz | head -5  # List archive contents
Complete One-Liner Alternative
bash
sudo tar -czf /home/jim.tar.gz /data/jim && echo "Archive created successfully!"
Expected Output
text
jim/
jim/file1.txt
jim/documents/
jim/documents/report.pdf
...
Verification Checklist
✅ jim.tar.gz exists in /home

✅ Archive contains complete /data/jim directory structure

✅ File is properly compressed (.tar.gz)

✅ Permissions allow task validation
​

Learning Outcomes
Linux tar command with gzip compression

File/directory operations between paths

Archive verification techniques

Status: Completed ✅
Portfolio Addition: Demonstrates Linux administration skills for DevOps roles
